Preschool Extended Day Survey

We are pleased to have your child attend our Preschool Program. The full-day program will run daily from 8:00 am until 2:00 pm. In consideration of those preschool students who are dismissed with their older siblings and the newly created aftercare program, our district is offering an extended day (2:00 pm until 2:40 pm) for those preschool students who have school-aged siblings, those who ride the Base bus, or those who are attending the tuition-based aftercare program. In order to take advantage of the extended day, we ask that you complete this form by Tuesday, August 27, 2019. Click here to access the form.

post_text:
Free Full-Day Preschool for Three and Four Year Old Students!
We are very pleased to share that the Lakehurst School District will continue to receive additional funding from the Department of Early Childhood Education to maintain our expanded preschool programs! Six (6) classroom sections for preschoolers will be available for the 2019-20 school year

If you are a legal resident of Lakehurst and/or are military connected/affiliated (i.e. military-federal government employee or contracted worker), and your child is turning three or four years of age on or by October 1, 2019, you may register your child(ren) for our expanded preschool programs by contacting Dr. Barneman, Assistant Superintendent (cbarneman@lakehurstschool.org) or Ms. Ward (cward@lakehurstschool.org) in the main office at (732) 657-5741.

post_text: At this time, the construction, rebuild, and remediation of the Lakehurst School District is moving along and our return date for the first week in January is still on target. Almost two-thirds of the asbestos abatement has been completed and floors are being prepped for the installation of tile. Our Lakehurst maintenance staff is doing an outstanding job with the painting of the entire building and making progress each day. It is really exciting to see things coming together and the anticipation continues to build for our return.
text: At this time, the construction, rebuild, and remediation of the Lakehurst School District is moving along and our return date for the first week in January is still on target. Almost two-thirds of the asbestos abatement has been completed and floors are being prepped for the installation of tile. Our Lakehurst maintenance staff is doing an outstanding job with the painting of the entire building and making progress each day. It is really exciting to see things coming together and the anticipation continues to build for our return.

post_text: After much consideration and thought it was determined that the entire student population, including preschool, will return to the building after the December break. It is in the best interest of the students and staff that they are not present during the asbestos remediation. The current placements and procedures will remain in place until our return to the Lakehurst Elementary School building in January. Thank you for your continued support and cooperation.

post_text: Today the district was in receipt of preliminary results from TTI Environmental regarding the mold testing that was completed throughout the school building. At this time the school building will remain closed until mold remediation occurs and we can ensure that the building is safe for students and staff. The students will begin school as scheduled, however we will be utilizing space at both St. John’s Church in Lakehurst and Manchester Schools. A Special Emergency Board of Education meeting is scheduled for 6:30 tomorrow night at the Lakehurst Community Center. We will be discussing the findings of the testing and the educational plan for our students. If you are unavailable to attend an update will be provided on our website following the meeting. Please feel free to email questions prior to the meeting or if you are unable to attend to lfuhring@lakehurstschool.org so that we are prepared to comprehensively provide information and address any questions or concerns. Thank you!

post_text: Good evening, the administration met with TTI Environmentalists this morning to determine necessary steps. TTI professionals will conduct testing in order to characterize the building and create an action plan. We anticipate this information will be available by the end of the weekend and will provide those updates to families and the community as soon as we are in receipt of the reports. Thank you for your continued patience as we work through this situation and ensure the safety and well-being of all of our students and staff.

post_text:
Full-day Preschool Expansion Announcement

We are very pleased to share in the exciting news that Lakehurst School District has received additional preschool funding to expand our preschool programs! Starting October 10, 2017, the district will open an additional section for 4-year old preschoolers AND we are partnering with OCEAN Inc./Headstart (Manchester) to provide a full-day 3-year old preschool program.

If you are a legal resident of Lakehurst and/or are military connected and you have a child that is turning three or four years of age on or by October 1, 2017, you may register your child(ren) for the expanded preschool programs by contacting Ms. Ward in the main office at (732) 657-5741. Registration materials will be posted shortly.

post_text: Looking forward to some great initiatives we will be starting through the technology class this year.
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Caine's Arcade

Lakehurst Elementary School
August 1, 2016 at 7:08 AM ·

In the fall, students in at least grades 3-5 will be participating in the Global Cardboard Challenge in technology and STEM classes, started by the Imagination Foundation.
This activity will help to build engineering, design-thinking, and problem-solving skills in a creative way. Students will be able to join and collaborate with students worldwide.
Feel free to view the video that inspired the movement: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=faIFNkdq96U.

If you have extra cardboard or tape that you can spare, please drop it off at the main office anytime, Mon-Thurs, before 3PM during the summer. Thank you for your support.

The Lakehurst Borough Police Department and the Lakehurst Youth and Recreation are hosting its annual bicycle rodeo. The rodeo is open to all children grades Pre-K through 8th. The event will include a bicycle safety check, agility course, and a race around the lake with prizes awarded to participants. Free food and drinks will be provided. All participants must have a helmet. For further information, contact Officer James at (732) 657-7812 ext 314.
Flyer can be downloaded here: http://lakehurstschool.org/site/handlers/filedownload.ashx?moduleinstanceid=1629&dataid=2572&FileName=Bicycle%20Rodeo%20Flyer.pdf

post_text: The Cat in the Hat stopped by Lakehurst Elementary School to help announce the winners of their annual Read Across America Read-A-Thon. There was an individual winner for each grade level, Preschool-4th Grade, and the two classes with the most cumulative reading hours received pizza parties from the PTA. It was a fun and energized week that motivated all of the students to read an incredibly impressive amount of hours!

Lakehurst Comprehensive Needs Assessment
Your thoughts and ideas are important to the continued success of the Lakehurst Elementary School District. post_text: Mrs. Bayne’s class participated in the 2015 Barnegat Bay Blitz Rain Barrel Challenge. The voting is open and ends on May 1st. If our school wins, Lakehurst Elementary School will get a free Barnegat Bay Blitz Festival. This festival will teach our students about the environment and how to protect the Barnegat Bay watershed. Please go to http://www.nj.gov/dep/barnegatbay/rbcvote2015.htm and vote for barrel #5. The students worked very hard and they also have a vegetable garden and have been learning about gardening, composting and living a greener life.

post_text:
Living Literature, Not Just Reading It
Students in Mrs. Kotch's class are reading Nathaniel Philbrick's "In the Heart of the Sea" about whalers in the 1820's. Their ship was attacked and sunk by a sperm whale 2000 miles off the coast of Chile in the Pacific Ocean. The true story follows their ordeal as they try to get home in three small rowboats, facing starvation, dehydration, and decisions that test their own morals. While at sea for up to 2 years at a time, sailors would pass time whittling and embroidering as they awaited their next kill. The students learned how to embroider as the whalers did, with just a piece of muslin, a needle and colored thread. The pieces will be on display in the hallway once they are completed.

post_text:
The sixth grade started learning about 3D printing in technology today. After an introduction to basic concepts, they leveled the build plate, setup the filament, and started a test print.
Soon they will start learning to build their own 3D designs.
